cp|1|fp|1|va|6|at|^-How Should You Respond to Opener's Reverse Bid?
^-|ht|c|cs||fp||cp||AT|^B@2^*BMM:^*N Howard Schutzman, BBO nickname, (hondo717) sat with the Movie Maker answering to, "How Should You Respond to Opener's Reverse Bid?" The following is a summary from that meeting. |
PG| ***** 0 ***** |


cs||FP||cp|8|AT|

^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|This is the area where many partnerships, even experienced ones, have the most difficulty. Here is the basic problem. In most auctions, one person takes charge (most often the responder), and drives the partnership to the appropriate contract. However, with reverse auctions, there is a lot of ambiguity regarding whether or not the partnership should be in game, and who is in charge. If the responder has 9+ points, then he or she needs to take charge to make sure the partnership gets to game. If the opener has a very good hand (18+), then he or she needs to take charge and make sure game is bid. However, when neither partner has game forcing values, or both partners have game forcing values, the auction can get confusing. |
PG| ***** 1 ***** |


cp|8|AT|

^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|There is no universal agreement on how to handle this problem. I am going to present the method I use, which I find both simple and effective. First of all, what are responder's obligations when opener makes a reverse bid? The simplest way to play is that it is a one round force for responder. Responder must make one more bid. Some people also play that the auction cannot stop below 2NT. That is a reasonable way to play, as it gives more flexibility in some auctions, but is not crucial.|
PG| ***** 2 ***** |


NT||
