cp|1|fp|1|va|6|at|^-How Should You Respond to Opener's Reverse Bid?
^-|at|^-With non-game forcing values (less than 9 points)
^-|ht|d|fp||cp|8|AT|^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|With non-game forcing values (less than 9 points), responder should make one of the following bids (all of which are not forcing, and can be passed):|
PG| ***** 3 ***** |


ht|h|cs|6|at|^b{|ia|,1dp1sp2hp3d|at|}|ht|h|at|^m@2^*BA.^*N Show a preference for one of opener's suits—diamonds here.|
PG| ***** 4 ***** |


ht|m|cs|6|at|^b{|ia|,1CP1SP2DP2S|at|}|ht|m|at|^m@2^*BB.^*N. Rebid responder's suit—spades.|
PG| ***** 5 ***** |


 

ht|r|cs|6|at|^b{|ia|,1CP1SP2HP2NT|at|}|ht|r|at|^m@2@2^*BC. ^*N.Rebid 2NT, showing a so so stopper in the 4th suit.|
PG| ***** 6 ***** |


NT||
%%%
cp|1|fp|1|va|6|at|^-How Should You Respond to Opener's Reverse Bid?
^-|at|^-With game forcing values (9 or more points)
^-|ht|d|fp||cp|8|AT|^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|With game forcing values, the key thing to remember is that if, as responder you have a game forcing hand, you must make a bid that communicates that to opener. The only non-game bid that is forcing is the 4th suit. If you make any other non-game bid, opener can pass. Therefore, with game forcing values (9 or more points) I recommend:|
PG| ***** 7 ***** |


 

ht|h|cs|6|at|^b{|ia|,1DP1SP2HP4H|at|}|ht|h|at|^m^*BA.^*N Jump to game in one of opener's suits—hearts here.|
PG| ***** 8 ***** |


ht|m|cs|6|at|^b{|ia|,1CP1SP2HP3NT|at|}|ht|m|at|^m^*BB.^*N Bid 3NT with stoppers in the 4th suit.|
PG| ***** 9 ***** |


 

ht|s|cs|6|at|^b{|ia|,1CP1SP2DP2H|at|}|ht|s|at|^m^*BC.^*N Bid the 4th (2@H) suit as an artificial bid to establish a game force.|
PG| ***** 10 ***** |


  
 
HT|x|cp|8|AT|^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|While it is true that, occasionally, bidding the 4th suit makes the auction difficult (particularly if is a major at the 3-level), my experience is that this approach is simple, unambiguous, and works very well on most hands. It pretty much always gets you to a reasonable contract.|
PG| ***** 11 ***** |


NT||
