cp|1|fp|1|va|6|at|^-How Should You Respond to Opener's Reverse Bid?
^-|ht|c|cp||fp||AT|^B@2^*BMM:^*N|cs|6|fp|3|at|^d{ Do you mind telling us about opener's third bid? }|
PG| ***** 12 ***** |


ht|e|cp|8|AT|^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|After responder makes a non-game forcing bid, opener's choices are:|
ht|f|cs|6|at|^b{|ia|,1CP1SP2HP3CPPP|at|}|ht|e|at|^m@2^Y@3^*BA.^*N If responder has taken a preference to one of opener's suits, with a minimum reverse (less than a good 18), opener will pass.|
PG| ***** 13 ***** |


ht|l|at|^B@2All non-game bids by opener show a game forcing hand. The main use of this principle is to allow opener to show delayed support for responder's major, giving the partnership a choice of 4 of the major, 3NT, or returning to opener's suit. For example in the auction below,|
ht|o|cs|6|at|^b{|ia|,1CP1SP2HP3CP3S|at|}|ht|n|at|^m@2^Y@3^*B3@S^*N is forcing.|
pg| ***** 14 ***** |


ht|u|cs|6|at|^b{|ia|,1DP1SP2HP2SP3D|at|}|ht|t|at|^m@2^Y@3If responder has rebid his suit, opener often passes, makes an invitational raise, or bids game. The only non-game bid that establishes a game force is the 4th suit. All other non-game bids are usually passed by responder. So, for example, the auction on the left is to play.|
PG| ***** 15 ***** |


NT|| 
%%% 
cp|1|fp|1|va|6|at|^-How Should You Respond to Opener's Reverse Bid?
^-|cp||fp||
ht|c|cs|6|at|^b{|ia|,1DP1SP2HP2SP3C|at|}|ht|b|at|^m@2^Y@3On the other hand, in the auction on the left 3@C establishes a game force.|
PG| ***** 16 ***** |


AT|

If responder bids 2NT, the only non-forcing bid is a correction to 3 of opener's first suit. All other bids establish a game force.|
pg| ***** 17 ***** |


 

ht|i|cs|6|at|^b{|ia|,1DP1SP2HP2NP3D|at|}|ht|h|at|^m@2^Y@3So, for example, in this auction on the left 3@D is to play.|
PG| ***** 18 ***** |


ht|o|cs|6|at|^b{|ia|,1DP1SP2HP2NP3S|at|}|ht|o|at|^m@2^Y@3On the other hand, in the auction on the left 3@S establishes a game force; responder usually bids either 3NT or 4@S. As a general rule, if, as responder, you are not sure whether the third bid by opener is forcing or not, assume it is forcing. |
PG| ***** 19 ***** |


ht|v|cs|6|at|^b{|ia|,1CP1SP2HP3CP3S|at|}|ht|v|at|^m@2^Y@3Watch out for the auction on the left which comes up frequently. It is when opener makes a delayed preference to responder's suit. That is forcing. |
PG| ***** 20 ***** |


